def binarize_images(sample):
    return (np.array(sample['image']) > 127).astype(np.uint8)
In[7]:
def display_n_sample_records(X_data: np.array, Y_data: np.array, n: int) -> None:
    image_indices = np.random.choice(range(X_data.shape[0]), n, replace = False)
    images = X_data[image_indices]
    labels = Y_data[image_indices]
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, n, figsize = (15, 5))
    for i in range(n):
        axes[i].imshow(images[i], cmap = 'gray')
        axes[i].set_title(f'Label: {labels[i]}')
        axes[i].axis('off')
    plt.show()

  • LogisticRegression as a classifier
In[18]:

logistic = LogisticRegression(random_state = 42)

pipeline = Pipeline(steps = [('rbm', rbm), ('logistic', logistic)])

The obtained hyperparameter values are the same across all datasets. Therefore, these values are discussed in this section. The parameter logistic__C = 0.1 indicates strong regularization in logistic regression, helping to prevent overfitting. The value rbm__batch_size = 10 means the RBM updates weights more frequently, balancing stability and training speed. The learning rate rbm__learning_rate = 0.05 allows moderately fast weight adjustments without risking instability. Lastly, rbm__n_components = 70 defines the dimensionality of the feature space, enabling a rich representation while minimizing the risk of overfitting. This configuration ensures a balance between the model's ability to learn complex patterns and its capacity to generalize effectively.

1.7 Perform classification on the test set and present detailed results (accuracy, precision, recall, f1-score):

  • At the level of each class
  • Aggregate

There is the classification_report() function, which partially returns the expected results. However, it does not completely satisfy the task e.g there is no accuracy for each class, so I am going to implement it from scratch.

In[44]:
def calc_metrics(TP: int, FP: int, FN: int, TN: int) -> tuple:
    accuracy = (TP + TN) / (TP + FP + FN + TN) if (TP + FP + FN + TN) > 0 else 0
    precision = TP / (TP + FP) if (TP + FP) > 0 else 0
    recall = TP / (TP + FN) if (TP + FN) > 0 else 0
    f1_score = 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall) if (precision + recall) > 0 else 0
    return accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score

def show_classification_metrics(Y_test: np.ndarray, Y_pred: np.ndarray) -> None:
    metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['accuracy', 'precision', 'recall', 'f1-score'])
    total_TP, total_FP, total_FN, total_TN = 0, 0, 0, 0

    for cls in np.unique(Y_test):
        TP = np.sum((Y_test == cls) & (Y_pred == cls))
        FP = np.sum((Y_test != cls) & (Y_pred == cls))
        FN = np.sum((Y_test == cls) & (Y_pred != cls))
        TN = np.sum((Y_test != cls) & (Y_pred != cls))

        total_TP += TP
        total_FP += FP
        total_FN += FN
        total_TN += TN

        accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score = calc_metrics(TP, FP, FN, TN)

        new_row = pd.DataFrame({'accuracy': [accuracy], 'precision': [precision], 'recall': [recall], 'f1-score': [f1_score]})
        metrics_df = pd.concat([metrics_df, new_row], ignore_index = True)

    total_accuracy, total_precision, total_recall, total_f1_score = calc_metrics(total_TP, total_FP, total_FN, total_TN)
    new_row = pd.DataFrame({'accuracy': [total_accuracy], 'precision': [total_precision], 'recall': [total_recall], 'f1-score': [total_f1_score]},
                          index = ['aggregated'])
    metrics_df = pd.concat([metrics_df, new_row], ignore_index = False)
    display(metrics_df)

1.9 Visualize all extracted hidden features (n components of images corresponding to learned weights associated with a specific hidden layer element). Try to recognize which high-level image features are enhanced by a specific component.

In[122]:
def visualize_extracted_hidden_features(sklearn_pipeline: Pipeline) -> None:
    n_components, n_vector = sklearn_pipeline['rbm'].components_.shape
    image_height, image_width = int(np.sqrt(n_vector)), int(np.sqrt(n_vector))

    plt.figure(figsize = (8, 8))
    for i, comp in enumerate(sklearn_pipeline['rbm'].components_):
        plt.subplot(n_components // 10, 10, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(comp.reshape(image_height, image_width), cmap = plt.cm.gray_r, interpolation = 'nearest')
        plt.xticks(())
        plt.yticks(())

    plt.suptitle(f'{n_components} components extracted by RBM', fontsize = 16, y = 0.9)
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace = 0.3, wspace = 0.1)
    plt.show()

2. Hierarchical Feature Extraction Using Deep Belief Network

In this section, we will check whether stacking multiple RBMs, i.e. building a Deep Belief Network model (and hierarchical feature extraction), will improve the previously obtained classification results. As in the previous task, the experiments should be performed for all datasets listed in point 3, with the MNIST and Fashion-MNIST datasets being mandatory.

2.1 and 2.2 Configure 3 RBMs so that the hidden layer of RBM(i) becomes the input layer (visible layer) of BRM(i + 1). The RBMs are trained in sequential order: 1, 2, 3. The hidden layer size is predefined, for example for MNIST we suggest: 256, 128, 64. For other data sets you can adjust these sizes empirically, but grid search is not required (high computational requirements). The values of the remaining hyperparameters can be similar to those in the previous task.

In[32]:
def classify_with_dbn(X_train: np.ndarray, Y_train: np.ndarray, X_test: np.ndarray, components_list: list) -> np.ndarray:
    rbms = []
    hidden_features_train = X_train
    hidden_features_test = X_test

    for i in range(len(components_list)):
        rbm = BernoulliRBM(n_components = components_list[i], batch_size = 10, learning_rate = 0.05, random_state = 42)
        hidden_features_train = rbm.fit_transform(hidden_features_train)
        rbms.append(rbm)

    logistic = LogisticRegression(C = 0.1, random_state = 42)
    logistic.fit(hidden_features_train, Y_train)

    for rbm in rbms:
        hidden_features_test = rbm.transform(hidden_features_test)

    return logistic.predict(hidden_features_test)

2.4 Is setting RBM extractors beneficial for each dataset? When can hierarchical feature extraction be useful?

The effectiveness of setting RBM extractors depends on the dataset and its inherent structure. The results show that RBM extractors were not universally beneficial across all datasets. For MNIST and Kuzushiji-MNIST, the application of RBM extractors proved to be advantageous, enhancing the classification results compared to the baseline in most cases. However, there was an exception with the first RBM, which did not always provide an improvement.

In contrast, for Fashion-MNIST and Kuzushiji-49, using RBM extractors resulted in worse accuracy than the baseline. This decline was particularly evident in Fashion-MNIST, where each additional RBM led to progressively worse results. This suggests that RBM extractors were unable to capture meaningful features for these datasets or caused the model to overfit the training data.

Summarizing, hierarchical feature extraction may not always be beneficial. For datasets without clear hierarchical structures or those with very complex features (like Fashion-MNIST), the extracted features may not generalize well, leading to degraded performance.

Hierarchical feature extraction, as implemented through stacked RBMs, can be useful in specific scenarios. It is particularly effective when working with datasets that have complex, layered structures, such as:

  • visual datasets with hierarchical features e.g. MNIST,
  • datasets with significant noise - RBMs may help filter out irrelevant features, retaining only the most important aspects of the data,
  • dimensionality reduction tasks - RBMs can compactly represent high-dimensional data while preserving the key information needed for classification.

3. Restricted Boltzmann Machines: Implementation, Reconstruction Tests

3.1 Implement RBM with the Contrastive Divergence training algorithm.

In[205]:
class RBM():
    def __init__(self, visible_dim, hidden_dim):
        self.visible_dim = visible_dim
        self.hidden_dim = hidden_dim
        self.weights = np.random.randn(visible_dim, hidden_dim)
        self.biases_hidden = np.random.randn(hidden_dim)
        self.biases_visible = np.random.randn(visible_dim)
    
    def fit(self, X, epochs = 10, batch_dim = 50, lr = 0.1):
        for epoch in range(epochs):
            self.plot_weights(step = epoch, save = True)
            error_epoch = 0
            batches = list(gen_batches(X.shape[0], batch_dim))

            for batch in batches:
                batch = X[batch.start:batch.stop]
                batch_size = batch.shape[0]
                
                ones_poshidP = np.ones((batch_size, self.hidden_dim))
                poshidP = ones_poshidP/(ones_poshidP + np.exp(-np.dot(batch,self.weights) - self.biases_hidden))
                wake = np.dot(batch.T, poshidP)
                
                ones_reconDataP = np.ones((batch_size, self.visible_dim))
                reconDataP = ones_reconDataP / (ones_reconDataP + np.exp(-np.dot(poshidP, np.transpose(self.weights)) - self.biases_visible))
                ones_neghidP = np.ones((batch_size, self.hidden_dim))
                neghidP = ones_neghidP / (ones_neghidP + np.exp(-np.dot(reconDataP, self.weights) - self.biases_hidden))
                dream = np.dot(np.transpose(reconDataP), neghidP)
                error = np.sum((batch-reconDataP) ** 2)/batch_size
                
                self.weights += lr * (wake - dream) / batch_size
                self.biases_hidden += lr * (np.sum(poshidP - neghidP, axis = 0)) / batch_size
                self.biases_visible += lr * (np.sum(batch - reconDataP, axis = 0)) / batch_size

                error_epoch += error
            
            error_epoch /= len(batches)
            print(f"epoch: {epoch}/{epochs} \t{'error:'} {error_epoch}")

    def reconstruct(self, X):
        ones_poshidP = np.ones((X.shape[0], self.hidden_dim))
        poshidP = ones_poshidP / (ones_poshidP + np.exp(-np.dot(X,self.weights) - self.biases_hidden))
        poshidS = poshidP > np.random.uniform(size = poshidP.shape)

        ones_reconDataP = np.ones((X.shape[0], self.visible_dim))
        reconDataP = ones_reconDataP / (ones_reconDataP + np.exp(-np.dot(poshidS,np.transpose(self.weights)) - self.biases_visible))

        return reconDataP

    def plot_weights(self, title = 'weights', step = 0, save = True):
        cols = 5
        rows = int(self.hidden_dim / cols)
        
        plt.clf()
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, cols, figsize = (10, 10))
        fig.suptitle(f'{title} step:{step}')
        for i in range(rows):
            for j in range(cols):
                axes[i, j].imshow(self.weights[:, i * cols + j].reshape(28, 28), cmap = 'gray')
                axes[i, j].axis('off')

        plt.subplots_adjust(wspace = 1, hspace = 1)

        if save:
            plt.savefig(f'{title}_step_{step}.png')
        else:
            plt.show()

        plt.close()

4.2 Build and train a simple Autoencoder. Example configuration of a simple Autoencoder:

  • Encoding: ReLU activation
  • Decoding: sigmoid activation
  • Adam optimizer
  • Loss function: binary crossentropy
  • Encoding dimension: 196 (number of extracted features)
  • Number of training epochs: > 30
In[15]:
class Autoencoder(Model):
    def __init__(self, latent_dim):
        super(Autoencoder, self).__init__()
        self.latent_dim = latent_dim   
        self.encoder = tf.keras.Sequential([
            layers.Flatten(),
            layers.Dense(latent_dim, activation = 'relu'),
        ])
        self.decoder = tf.keras.Sequential([
            layers.Dense(784, activation = 'sigmoid'),
            layers.Reshape((28, 28, 1))
        ])

    def call(self, x):
        encoded = self.encoder(x)
        decoded = self.decoder(encoded)
        return decoded
